<Link id="l00316" /><CodeLine lineNumber="316"><Highlight kind="comment">/&#42;&#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00317" /><CodeLine lineNumber="317"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; An opaque lookup state object. Instances of this type can be captured to</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00318" /><CodeLine lineNumber="318"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; suspend a lookup while a custom generator function attempts to produce a</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00319" /><CodeLine lineNumber="319"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; definition.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00320" /><CodeLine lineNumber="320"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00321" /><CodeLine lineNumber="321"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; If a client captures a lookup state object then they must eventually call</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00322" /><CodeLine lineNumber="322"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; LLVMOrcLookupStateContinueLookup to restart the lookup. This is required</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00323" /><CodeLine lineNumber="323"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; in order to release memory allocated for the lookup state, even if errors</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00324" /><CodeLine lineNumber="324"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; have occurred while the lookup was suspended (if these errors have made the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00325" /><CodeLine lineNumber="325"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; lookup impossible to complete then it will issue its own error before</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00326" /><CodeLine lineNumber="326"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; destruction).</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00327" /><CodeLine lineNumber="327"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;/</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00328" /><CodeLine lineNumber="328" lineLink="/docs/api/groups/llvmcexecutionengineorc/#gae1baa3cd8ebe2bafcd4e202f3d9dd416"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">typedef</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">struct </Highlight><Highlight kind="normal">LLVMOrcOpaqueLookupState &#42;<a href="/docs/api/groups/llvmcexecutionengineorc/#gae1baa3cd8ebe2bafcd4e202f3d9dd416">LLVMOrcLookupStateRef</a>;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00330" /><CodeLine lineNumber="330"><Highlight kind="comment">/&#42;&#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00331" /><CodeLine lineNumber="331"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; A custom generator function. This can be used to create a custom generator</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00332" /><CodeLine lineNumber="332"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; object using LLVMOrcCreateCustomCAPIDefinitionGenerator. The resulting</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00333" /><CodeLine lineNumber="333"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; object can be attached to a JITDylib, via LLVMOrcJITDylibAddGenerator, to</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00334" /><CodeLine lineNumber="334"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; receive callbacks when lookups fail to match existing definitions.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00335" /><CodeLine lineNumber="335"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00336" /><CodeLine lineNumber="336"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; GeneratorObj will contain the address of the custom generator object.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00337" /><CodeLine lineNumber="337"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00338" /><CodeLine lineNumber="338"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; Ctx will contain the context object passed to</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00339" /><CodeLine lineNumber="339"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; LLVMOrcCreateCustomCAPIDefinitionGenerator.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00340" /><CodeLine lineNumber="340"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00341" /><CodeLine lineNumber="341"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; LookupState will contain a pointer to an LLVMOrcLookupStateRef object. This</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00342" /><CodeLine lineNumber="342"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; can optionally be modified to make the definition generation process</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00343" /><CodeLine lineNumber="343"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; asynchronous: If the LookupStateRef value is copied, and the original</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00344" /><CodeLine lineNumber="344"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; LLVMOrcLookupStateRef set to null, the lookup will be suspended. Once the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00345" /><CodeLine lineNumber="345"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; asynchronous definition process has been completed clients must call</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00346" /><CodeLine lineNumber="346"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; LLVMOrcLookupStateContinueLookup to continue the lookup (this should be</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00347" /><CodeLine lineNumber="347"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; done unconditionally, even if errors have occurred in the mean time, to</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00348" /><CodeLine lineNumber="348"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; free the lookup state memory and notify the query object of the failures).</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00349" /><CodeLine lineNumber="349"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; If LookupState is captured this function must return LLVMErrorSuccess.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00350" /><CodeLine lineNumber="350"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00353" /><CodeLine lineNumber="353"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00354" /><CodeLine lineNumber="354"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The JD argument specifies which JITDylib the definitions should be generated</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00355" /><CodeLine lineNumber="355"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; into.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00356" /><CodeLine lineNumber="356"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00357" /><CodeLine lineNumber="357"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The JDLookupFlags argument can be inspected to determine whether the original</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00358" /><CodeLine lineNumber="358"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; lookup included non-exported symbols.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00359" /><CodeLine lineNumber="359"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00428" /><CodeLine lineNumber="428"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; returns to the caller and the function does not need to do any lifetime</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00429" /><CodeLine lineNumber="429"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; management.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00430" /><CodeLine lineNumber="430"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00543" /><CodeLine lineNumber="543"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; names that they wish to hold after the function returns.</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00549" /><CodeLine lineNumber="549"><Highlight kind="comment">/&#42;&#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00550" /><CodeLine lineNumber="550"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; Look up symbols in an execution session.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00551" /><CodeLine lineNumber="551"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00552" /><CodeLine lineNumber="552"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; This is a wrapper around the general ExecutionSession::lookup function.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00553" /><CodeLine lineNumber="553"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00554" /><CodeLine lineNumber="554"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The SearchOrder argument contains a list of (JITDylibs, JITDylibSearchFlags)</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00555" /><CodeLine lineNumber="555"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; pairs that describe the search order. The JITDylibs will be searched in the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00556" /><CodeLine lineNumber="556"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; given order to try to find the symbols in the Symbols argument.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00557" /><CodeLine lineNumber="557"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00558" /><CodeLine lineNumber="558"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The Symbols argument should contain a null-terminated array of</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00559" /><CodeLine lineNumber="559"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; (SymbolStringPtr, SymbolLookupFlags) pairs describing the symbols to be</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00560" /><CodeLine lineNumber="560"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; searched for. This function takes ownership of the elements of the Symbols</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00561" /><CodeLine lineNumber="561"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; array. The Name fields of the Symbols elements are taken to have been</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00562" /><CodeLine lineNumber="562"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; retained by the client for this function. The client should &#42;not&#42; release the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00563" /><CodeLine lineNumber="563"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; Name fields, but are still responsible for destroying the array itself.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00564" /><CodeLine lineNumber="564"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00565" /><CodeLine lineNumber="565"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The HandleResult function will be called once all searched for symbols have</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00566" /><CodeLine lineNumber="566"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; been found, or an error occurs. The HandleResult function will be passed an</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00567" /><CodeLine lineNumber="567"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; LLVMErrorRef indicating success or failure, and (on success) a</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00568" /><CodeLine lineNumber="568"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; null-terminated LLVMOrcCSymbolMapPairs array containing the function result,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00569" /><CodeLine lineNumber="569"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; and the Ctx value passed to the lookup function.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00570" /><CodeLine lineNumber="570"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00571" /><CodeLine lineNumber="571"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The client is fully responsible for managing the lifetime of the Ctx object.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00572" /><CodeLine lineNumber="572"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; A common idiom is to allocate the context prior to the lookup and deallocate</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00573" /><CodeLine lineNumber="573"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; it in the handler.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00574" /><CodeLine lineNumber="574"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00575" /><CodeLine lineNumber="575"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; THIS API IS EXPERIMENTAL AND LIKELY TO CHANGE IN THE NEAR FUTURE!</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00576" /><CodeLine lineNumber="576"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;/</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00630" /><CodeLine lineNumber="630"><Highlight kind="comment">/&#42;&#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00631" /><CodeLine lineNumber="631"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; Create a custom MaterializationUnit.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00632" /><CodeLine lineNumber="632"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00633" /><CodeLine lineNumber="633"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; Name is a name for this MaterializationUnit to be used for identification</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00634" /><CodeLine lineNumber="634"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; and logging purposes (e.g. if this MaterializationUnit produces an</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00635" /><CodeLine lineNumber="635"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; object buffer then the name of that buffer will be derived from this name).</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00636" /><CodeLine lineNumber="636"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00637" /><CodeLine lineNumber="637"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The Syms list contains the names and linkages of the symbols provided by this</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00638" /><CodeLine lineNumber="638"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; unit. This function takes ownership of the elements of the Syms array. The</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00639" /><CodeLine lineNumber="639"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; Name fields of the array elements are taken to have been retained for this</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00640" /><CodeLine lineNumber="640"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; function. The client should &#42;not&#42; release the elements of the array, but is</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00641" /><CodeLine lineNumber="641"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; still responsible for destroying the array itself.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00642" /><CodeLine lineNumber="642"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00643" /><CodeLine lineNumber="643"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The InitSym argument indicates whether or not this MaterializationUnit</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00644" /><CodeLine lineNumber="644"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; contains static initializers. If three are no static initializers (the common</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00645" /><CodeLine lineNumber="645"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; case) then this argument should be null. If there are static initializers</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00646" /><CodeLine lineNumber="646"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; then InitSym should be set to a unique name that also appears in the Syms</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00647" /><CodeLine lineNumber="647"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; list with the LLVMJITSymbolGenericFlagsMaterializationSideEffectsOnly flag</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00648" /><CodeLine lineNumber="648"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; set. This function takes ownership of the InitSym, which should have been</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00649" /><CodeLine lineNumber="649"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; retained twice on behalf of this function: once for the Syms entry and once</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00650" /><CodeLine lineNumber="650"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; for InitSym. If clients wish to use the InitSym value after this function</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00651" /><CodeLine lineNumber="651"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; returns they must retain it once more for themselves.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00652" /><CodeLine lineNumber="652"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00653" /><CodeLine lineNumber="653"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; If any of the symbols in the Syms list is looked up then the Materialize</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00654" /><CodeLine lineNumber="654"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; function will be called.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00655" /><CodeLine lineNumber="655"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00656" /><CodeLine lineNumber="656"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; If any of the symbols in the Syms list is overridden then the Discard</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00657" /><CodeLine lineNumber="657"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; function will be called.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00658" /><CodeLine lineNumber="658"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00659" /><CodeLine lineNumber="659"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The caller owns the underling MaterializationUnit and is responsible for</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00660" /><CodeLine lineNumber="660"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; either passing it to a JITDylib (via LLVMOrcJITDylibDefine) or disposing</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00661" /><CodeLine lineNumber="661"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; of it by calling LLVMOrcDisposeMaterializationUnit.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00662" /><CodeLine lineNumber="662"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;/</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00663" /><CodeLine lineNumber="663"><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="/docs/api/groups/llvmcexecutionengineorc/#gaf17d82579d868fbdda47a32ad1cc08b4">LLVMOrcMaterializationUnitRef</a> <a href="/docs/api/groups/llvmcexecutionengineorc/#ga22d7fb042682841596db76f6513401cb">LLVMOrcCreateCustomMaterializationUnit</a>(</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00666" /><CodeLine lineNumber="666"><Highlight kind="normal">    <a href="/docs/api/groups/llvmcexecutionengineorc/#gacd70f412e613614839766293b19a1bc5">LLVMOrcMaterializationUnitMaterializeFunction</a> Materialize,</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00671" /><CodeLine lineNumber="671"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; Create a MaterializationUnit to define the given symbols as pointing to</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00672" /><CodeLine lineNumber="672"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; the corresponding raw addresses.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00673" /><CodeLine lineNumber="673"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00674" /><CodeLine lineNumber="674"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; This function takes ownership of the elements of the Syms array. The Name</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00675" /><CodeLine lineNumber="675"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; fields of the array elements are taken to have been retained for this</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00676" /><CodeLine lineNumber="676"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; function. This allows the following pattern...</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00677" /><CodeLine lineNumber="677"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00678" /><CodeLine lineNumber="678"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;   size&#95;t NumPairs;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00679" /><CodeLine lineNumber="679"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;   LLVMOrcCSymbolMapPairs Sym;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00680" /><CodeLine lineNumber="680"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;   -- Build Syms array --</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00681" /><CodeLine lineNumber="681"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;   LLVMOrcMaterializationUnitRef MU =</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00682" /><CodeLine lineNumber="682"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;       LLVMOrcAbsoluteSymbols(Syms, NumPairs);</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00683" /><CodeLine lineNumber="683"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00684" /><CodeLine lineNumber="684"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; ... without requiring cleanup of the elements of the Sym array afterwards.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00685" /><CodeLine lineNumber="685"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00686" /><CodeLine lineNumber="686"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The client is still responsible for deleting the Sym array itself.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00687" /><CodeLine lineNumber="687"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00688" /><CodeLine lineNumber="688"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; If a client wishes to reuse elements of the Sym array after this call they</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00689" /><CodeLine lineNumber="689"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; must explicitly retain each of the elements for themselves.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00690" /><CodeLine lineNumber="690"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;/</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00691" /><CodeLine lineNumber="691"><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="/docs/api/groups/llvmcexecutionengineorc/#gaf17d82579d868fbdda47a32ad1cc08b4">LLVMOrcMaterializationUnitRef</a></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01001" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1001"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; the JITDylib. On success the resulting generator is owned by the client.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01002" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1002"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; Ownership is typically transferred by adding the instance to a JITDylib</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01003" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1003"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; using LLVMOrcJITDylibAddGenerator,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01004" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1004"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01005" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1005"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The GlobalPrefix argument specifies the character that appears on the front</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01006" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1006"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; of linker-mangled symbols for the target platform (e.g. &#39;&#95;&#39; on MachO).</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01007" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1007"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; If non-null, this character will be stripped from the start of all symbol</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01008" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1008"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; strings before passing the remaining substring to dlsym.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01009" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1009"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01010" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1010"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The optional Filter and Ctx arguments can be used to supply a symbol name</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01011" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1011"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; filter: Only symbols for which the filter returns true will be visible to</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01012" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1012"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; JIT&#39;d code. If the Filter argument is null then all process symbols will</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01013" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1013"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; be visible to JIT&#39;d code. Note that the symbol name passed to the Filter</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01014" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1014"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; function is the full mangled symbol: The client is responsible for stripping</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01015" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1015"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; the global prefix if present.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01016" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1016"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;/</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l01023" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1023"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; library symbols into the JITDylib. On success the resulting generator is</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01024" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1024"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; owned by the client. Ownership is typically transferred by adding the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01025" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1025"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; instance to a JITDylib using LLVMOrcJITDylibAddGenerator,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01026" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1026"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01027" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1027"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The GlobalPrefix argument specifies the character that appears on the front</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01028" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1028"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; of linker-mangled symbols for the target platform (e.g. &#39;&#95;&#39; on MachO).</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01029" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1029"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; If non-null, this character will be stripped from the start of all symbol</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01030" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1030"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; strings before passing the remaining substring to dlsym.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01031" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1031"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01032" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1032"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; The optional Filter and Ctx arguments can be used to supply a symbol name</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01033" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1033"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; filter: Only symbols for which the filter returns true will be visible to</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01034" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1034"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; JIT&#39;d code. If the Filter argument is null then all library symbols will</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01035" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1035"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; be visible to JIT&#39;d code. Note that the symbol name passed to the Filter</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01036" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1036"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; function is the full mangled symbol: The client is responsible for stripping</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01037" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1037"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; the global prefix if present.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01038" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1038"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; </Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l01039" /><CodeLine lineNumber="1039"><Highlight kind="comment"> &#42; THIS API IS EXPERIMENTAL AND LIKELY TO CHANGE IN THE NEAR FUTURE!</Highlight></CodeLine>
